    <section class="dishes">
        <div class="dish-card" id="sushi">
            <h3>Sushi</h3>
            <p>Sushi is a traditional Japanese dish made with vinegared rice, usually accompanied by a variety of
                ingredients such as raw fish, vegetables, and sometimes tropical fruits. The primary types of sushi
                include nigiri (hand-pressed sushi), maki (roll sushi), sashimi (slices of raw fish without rice), and
                temaki (hand-rolled sushi).
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn-order"><a href="#"><strong>Order Now</strong></a></button>
        </div>
        <div class="dish-card" id="ramen">
            <h3>Ramen</h3>
            <p>Ramen is a popular noodle soup dish in Japan. It consists of Chinese-style wheat noodles served in a
                meat or (occasionally) fish-based broth, often flavored with soy sauce or miso. Toppings commonly
                include sliced pork (chashu), nori (dried seaweed), menma (bamboo shoots), and green onions.
                There are many regional variations of ramen in Japan, each with its unique ingredients and flavors.
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn-order"><a href="#"><strong>Order Now</strong></a></button>
        </div>
        <div class="dish-card" id="tempura">
            <h3>Tempura</h3>
            <p>Tempura is a traditional Japanese dish where seafood, vegetables, or other ingredients are battered and
                deep-fried. The batter is made from cold water and wheat flour, sometimes with egg, resulting in a light
                and crispy texture. Common tempura ingredients include shrimp, squid, sweet potatoes, and bell peppers.
                Tempura is often served with tentsuyu dipping sauce, which is a mix of dashi, soy sauce, and mirin,
                along with grated daikon radish.
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn-order"><a href="#"><strong>Order Now</strong></a></button>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="about">
        <h1>More About This Cuisine</h1>
        <p>
            Japanese cuisine, also known as "Washoku," is renowned for its emphasis on seasonality, quality of
            ingredients, and presentation. Rooted in centuries-old traditions, it offers a unique and diverse
            culinary experience that reflects the rich culture and history of Japan.
        </p>
        <p>
            From the delicate flavors of sushi and sashimi to the hearty comfort of ramen and tempura, Japanese
            dishes are a perfect balance of taste and aesthetics. The use of fresh, natural ingredients and
            meticulous preparation methods ensure that every meal is a feast for both the eyes and the palate.
        </p>
        <p>
            Beyond its delicious food, Japanese cuisine also emphasizes the importance of dining etiquette and the
            enjoyment of food as a communal activity. Whether you're savoring a simple bowl of miso soup or
            indulging in a multi-course kaiseki meal, each dining experience is a celebration of Japan's culinary
            artistry.
        </p>
    </section>
